snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone wants to comment on shit like they’re the authority on a subject and place judgement on particular groups to feel better about themselves. One thing I’ve learned from reading these comments... people are cruel. Addiction doesn’t just have to be drugs. You can be addicted to your career, phone, people, food, perfection, etc. However we only feel a need to demonize, put down those with drug addictions... why is that? Why are y’all so comfortable saying they are scum as if you never did anything shameful in your life?

It’s one thing to point out another persons wrongs or mistakes but it’s a completely different thing to do it in such a way that paints you as superior or separate from them. Everyone does bad things, everyone makes mistakes to sit here trying to rank which ones are worse (which is essentially what you do by placing judgment) is stupid.

Because we are all human and all have brains, we all have the capacity to develop addiction, to lie, to murder, to steal, to cheat, to have a meltdown, etc. When we talk about people in terms of “us vs them” it’s easy to dehumanize and rationalize abuse towards them.

For example, my dad told me a bit about the crack epidemic of the 80s and how pretty much everyone who did crack was ostracized by their friends and community and treated badly. In some places this was even as bad as people spitting on them, beating them up, calling them crack heads etc. Of course because they are ostracized from the public usually they end up getting closer to other people who use and inevitably their addiction got worse and they died.
But my dad was different. He said he never turned on people he knew that got caught up in it. He would try to help them, talk to them, etc. My dad was actually able to convince this one guy to move south and stay with family there. & my dad said he saw that guy years later and he thanked my dad and told him he was able to get clean.

I’ve also personally known some addicts who were kinder and more genuine than some completely clean Christians I’ve met.

My point is...while it is no ones responsibility to help another person recover from addiction we certainly don’t help the process but being so cruel and isolating. It doesn’t take anything from you to be compassionate and speak to another person like a human being. It is possible to be supportive without putting yourself in jeopardy. You might even gain some knowledge and understanding in the process.


Just think... if we were all a little bit kinder and less bullying, maybe we would still have people like Amy Winehouse around!!!

Either way, I’m glad Taylor had loving and compassionate people around her to support her on her journey to health. I don’t see her as a blamer, attention seeker, or even a victim. She’s a warrior

“Choose life

Choose Facebook, Twitter, Instagram and hope that someone, somewhere cares

Choose looking up old flames, wishing you’d done it all differently

And choose watching history repeat itself

Choose your future

Choose reality TV, slut shaming, revenge porn

Choose a zero hour contract, a two hour journey to work

You’re an addict, so be addicted

Just be addicted to something else

Choose the ones you love

Choose your future

Choose life”
